  "local_port": 53896,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I do not have a surname on passport or any of my education certificates. What should be the most appropriate step now to fix the issue?",
  "response": "If you do not have a surname on your passport or education certificates and need to resolve this issue, consider the following steps:\n\n1. **Gather Documentation**: Collect all relevant documents (passport, birth certificate, education certificates) that you have, regardless of whether they have a surname or not.\n\n2. **Check Regulations**: Investigate the regulations in your country regarding names on official documents. Different countries have specific rules about how names should appear on legal documents.\n\n3. **Contact Relevant Authorities**: Reach out to the relevant authorities:\n   - **Passport Office**: If your passport lacks a surname, contact the passport issuing agency to inquire about the process for amending the passport. They may require specific documentation to process your request.\n   - **Educational Institutions**: Contact the schools or universities that issued your certificates. They may have procedures in place for correcting or amending the names on your educational records.\n\n4. **Legal Name Change**: If it's necessary to adopt a surname legally, you may need to go through a legal name change process. This typically involves:\n   - Filing a petition with your local court.\n   - Utilizing any required forms and paying applicable fees.\n   - Attending a court hearing, if necessary.\n\n5. **Update Legal Documents**: Once you have all your documents in order, ensure that any legal name changes are reflected everywhere\u2014this includes your passport, driver's license, and any other legal identification or records.\n\n6. **Consult a Legal Professional**: If you're uncertain about the process or feel that it might be complex, consulting with a legal professional may help guide you through it.\n\n7. **Keep Copies**: Throughout this process, make sure to keep copies of all correspondence and documents submitted or received for your records.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to address the issue of not having a surname on your documents.",
